<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="specPoint"><h2 id="the-need-for-a-circulatory-system">The Need for a Circulatory System</h2><ul><li><p>The cells of all living organisms need a <b>constant supply of reactants</b> for metabolism, e.g. oxygen and glucose</p></li><li><p>Single-celled organisms can gain oxygen and glucose directly from their surroundings, and the molecules can <b>diffuse to all parts of the cell quickly </b>due to <b>short diffusion distances</b></p></li><li><p>Larger organisms, however, are made up of many layers of cells, meaning that the time taken for substances such as glucose and oxygen to diffuse to every cell in the body would be far too long</p><ul><li><p>The diffusion distances involved are<b> too great</b></p></li><li><p>Large organisms often have<b> high energy requirements</b>, so the delivery of reactants for metabolism needs to happen quickly</p></li></ul></li><li><p>To solve this problem their exchange surfaces are connected to a <b>mass transport system</b>, for example:</p><ul><li><p>The digestive system is connected to the circulatory system</p></li><li><p>The lungs are connected to the circulatory system</p></li></ul></li><li><p><b>Mass transport</b> is the <b>bulk movement</b> of gases or liquids in <b>one direction</b>, usually via a system of vessels and tubes</p></li><li><p>The <b>circulatory system</b> in mammals is a well-studied example of a mass transport system; the one-way flow of blood within the blood vessels carries essential nutrients and gases to all the cells of the body</p></li><li><p>Mass transport systems help to</p><ul><li><p>Bring substances <b>quickly</b> from one exchange site to another</p></li><li><p><b>Maintain diffusion gradients</b> at exchange sites and between cells and their fluid surroundings</p></li><li><p>Ensure <b>effective cell activity</b> by supplying reactants and removing waste products</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="The double circulatory system in mammals" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1468" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/The-double-circulatory-system-in-mammals.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Mammals have a circulatory system known as a double circulatory system; the blood travels around the body in two separate circuits known as the pulmonary and systemic circulation</b></i></p></div></div></div>